review_blob: Cloudy yellowish body with a big quickly disappearing head.  Highly carbonated.  bitter and slightly sour.  Wasnt all that impressed, but it did go really good with a lemon bundt cake.
beer_name: Sierra Nevada / Russian River BRUX Domesticated Wild Ale

review_blob: Dark red in appearance.  the aroma has a hint of sweetness and a nice citrusy hop note.  The flavor is sweet and malty with an underlying hoppiness.

One of my favorite speedway variants.  The use of the Papua New Guinea coffee is just about perfect.  The Kopi Luawak is probably the only coffee addition Ive liked better.Earlier Rating: 10/20/2003 Total Score: 4.8The black as night body of this brew was topped by a medium thick head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass.  Slightly bitter malty aroma with notes of coffee and anise with a slight sweetness.  Slightly bitter coffee and malt flavor with a touch of anise, slight notes of alcohol and a subtle sweetness.  The finish is bitter and slightly roasty.  This is a thick full bodied brew with a creamy smoothness.
What a great variation on the little devil.  A nice touch of lactic acidity gives this beer the perfect amount of sourness.  Light and crispy...a great beer to drink on a hot day.
Full of scotch notes and a little boozie even compared to the Bourbon Barrel-Aged version.
Has all the great characteristics of the original Speedway but with a slight added chocolate bitterness that in my opinion takes away from the greatness of the original.
Flavor and Aroma are full of malty sweetness with notes of dark fruit and a hint of caramel.
The nose and flavor are full of a rich maltiness with notes of toffee, caramel and a nice but not overwhelming hoppiness.

nice vanilla notes are added to the chocolate and coffee notes typically found in Speedway.  Unfortunately, I cant get past the artificial vanilla flavor that I seem to pick up in all of the variants with vanilla in them.
Reminds me a little of chocolate covered cherries with a hint of coffee in there as well.
beer_name: AleSmith Speedway Stout - Rye Barrel Aged: Cherries

review_blob: Very nice blend of speedways...the bourbon notes are lighter than in the full on barrel aged version, but, still very nice.

Probably my least favorite of the Speedway variants.  Its cool and minty as expected, I just dont really like the mint in it. Still way better than other stouts Ive had with some type of mint added to it.
Vanilla and coconut notes abound with the usual chocolate and coffee notes underlying.  Again, I unfortunately feel like the vanilla tastes a little artificial.
This variant was definitely sweeter than the original and the coffee wasnt as prominent in my opinion.  Still a great beer as all the Speedway Variants are.
I really liked this one...It actually reminded me of one of those chocolate oranges.  Great orange notes and a nice chocolate note.
A pretty good variant of this beer.  Subtle chili pepper notes and a hint of added chocolate. I feel as though something was missing on this one...not quite sure what though.
Nice cinnamon and chocolate notes showing in this one which just adds to the complexity of an already amazing beer.

A nice little added bitter chocolate shows through with lots of vanilla.  I have to say, it would have gotten a higher rating if the vanilla didnt taste a little artificial to me.  Still a great beer.
beer_name: AleSmith Speedway Stout - Cacao Nibs & Vanilla Bean

review_blob: Not my favorite of the speedway variations, but, I get what they were going for.  The spiciness of the peppers comes through with subtlety, especially at the back end.
beer_name: AleSmith Speedway Stout - Chipotle & Morita Peppers

review_blob: A great brown ale aged in barrels?  Yes, please.  The bourbon notes ad a great complexity to the nutty, malty notes of this beer.  A little hot, but not overwhelming.  Im amazed at how much bourbon comes through with only 13 days in the barrel.  Thank you sir...may I have another.
beer_name: AleSmith Nut Brown Ale - Barrel Aged

review_blob: Probably the best stout I have had.  Dark and dank, with a beautiful brown head.  The aroma is full of amazing coffee scents.  the flavor is sweet and malty, roasty and full of coffee deliciousness.  To take one of the best imperial stouts in the world and add the Kopi Luwak coffee to it was brilliant.
Another good English yeast alternative to the regular Cal ale yeast offering.  Malty and smokey with a nice sweetness.
beer_name: AleSmith Wee Heavy Scotch Ale - All English

review_blob: I love their brown ale and to make it with the english yeast was a nice surprise.  A little sweeter and not as nutty.
beer_name: AleSmith Nut Brown Ale - All English (Draft Only)

review_blob: Im not a huge smoked beer fan, but this one had the right amount of smokiness behind a great barleywine base.  The hint of maple sweetness is a great added flavor.
Great session beer! Sweet and malty with a slight biscuity note and the perfect hint of hops. I drank the hell out of this beer while it was on tap at the brewery.
Nice change for the Cal ale yeast version.  Still malty with a little more biscuity notes.
Pours with a dark brown body topped by a thin head with some lacing.  Its bitter yet slightly sweet and spicy with a light roast.  Medium to full bodied and smooth.
beer_name: 21st Amendment / Firestone Walker / Stone El Camino (Un)Real Black Ale

review_blob: Pours with a clear, amber-brown body topped by a thin to medium thick head with some lacing.  Its slightly sweet with a sour undertone and a touch of coconut. light to medium bodied and dry.

Pours with a dark brown body topped by a thin head with a good amount of lacing. Its slightly sweet and yeasty with a light bitterness, light dark fruit notes and notes of spice.  Medium bodied and smooth yet slightly dry.
beer_name: New Belgium Lips of Faith - Dark Heather Saison

review_blob: Pours with a clear, pale yellow body topped by a white, medium thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its slightly sweet with grassy hop notes, slight brett notes and vinious notes.  Light to medium bodied and well carbonated.

beer_brewer_name: Pretty Things Beer and Ale Project
review_blob: Pours with a dark red-brown body topped by a thin to medium thick head with some lacing left on the glass.  Its slightly sweet and malty with a hint of sourness and bitterness, some floral and dark fruit notes.  Full bodied and smooth.

Pours with a golden body topped by a thin to medium thick head with some lacing.  Its slightly sweet with a light bitterness, a little sour apple and a brett funk, especially in the nose.  Light to medium bodied and smooth.
Pours with a dark brown body topped by a thin head with some lacing. Its sweet and malty with notes of dark fruit and a very light peaty, roast note.  Full bodied and smooth.

Pours with an ember-orange body topped by a medium thick head wtih a good amount of lacing.  Its slightly sweet yet hoppy with notes of citrus (lemon), a balanced bitterness and slight notes of tomato.  Its medium  bodied and well carbonated with a slight warming quality.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours with a golden orange body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lacing.  Its hoppy and full of grapefruit and light pine notes with a light malt background.  Full bodied, well carbonated and slightly warming.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: Pours with a black body topped by a thick, brown head with a good amount of lacing.  Sweet and malty with ash, vanilla, bourbon, coffee, sour and roasty notes.  Full bodied and smooth yet warming.

Pours with a black body topped by a thin to medium thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its sweet and malty with a slight chipotle note and a little coffee and a lite roast.  Full bodied, well carbonated and a touch warming.

Pours with an amber body topped by a thin to medium thick head with some lacing left behind.  Its sweet and malty with notes of caramel and fruit with a decent amount of underlying bitterness and resinous and citrusy hop notes.  Full bodied and oily smooth.

Pours with a dark brown body topped by a thin head with a good amount of lacing.  Its slightly sweet and malty with a light roasty bitterness and nice mocha notes.  Full bodied, creamy and well carbonated.

Pours with a slightly cloudy, golden body topped by a thin to medium thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its sweet and malty with notes of wine and yeast with a little bitterness.  Light bodied, highly carbonated and dry.
Pours with a golden orange body topped by a thin head with some lacing.  Its slightly sweet and malty with a slightly bitter and citrusy hop note.  Light to medium bodied, smooth and slightly dry.

Pours with a cloudy, golden body topped by a thick, lively and foamy head with some lacing left on the glass.  Its bitter and hoppy with a yeasty citrus note and an underlying light maltiness.  Light to medium bodied, dry and highly carbonated.
beer_name: Back Forty Naked Pig Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours with a clear, amber body topped by a thin to medium thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its hoppy and bitter with a light citrus note, a little mustiness, and a slight malt note.  Medium bodied, smooth and slightly warming.

Pours with a cloudy, golden body topped by a medium thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its sour with a hintof sweetness, a little rye and some mustiness.  Light to medium bodied, highly carbonated and dry.
Pours with a red body topped by a thick head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass.  Its slightly sweet and malty with strong anise notes and a touch of sourness.  Full bodied and harsh.

Pours with an amber body topped by a medium to thick head with a good amount of lacing.  Its sweet and malty with notes of candy sugar and light notes of vanilla.  Medium to full bodied, well carbonated and warming.
Pours with a golden body topped by a medium thick head with some lacing.  Its bitter and floral with a very light horse blanket and a touch of sweetness.  Light bodied, crisp and dry.

Served on Nitro.  Pours with a black body topped by a thick head with a good amount of lacing left on the glass.  Its slightly sweet and malty, full of vanilla bourbon notes and a light roast.  Full bodied, creamy and smooth.

Pours with a dark brown to black body topped by a thin, brown head with little lacing.  Its sweet and malty with notes of fruit and a light roasty coffee note.  The nose was much better than the corresponding flavor.  Medium to full bodied, smooth and a touch warming.

Sampled as Mavericks Obama Presidential Ale.  Pours with a golden body topped by a thick, foamy head with a good amount of lacing.  Hmmm...not much to say about it except it has a light grassy bitterness.  Light bodied and highly carbonated.
